A wedding quilt! Several years ago my friends asked if I could use some old shirts that were destined for the donation pile. I happily took them and (sort of jokingly, but also hopefully) promised if they ever got married, I’d make them a quilt. Well, their beautiful wedding took place last August (I even had the honour of my first-ever bridesmaid duty!), so I had to break my quilting fast and get busy!
👰🤵‍♂️
This is the third improv quilt I’ve made entirely from woven shirts. They’re all so soft and drapey. Like my “Casual Friday” quilt recently featured in @curatedquilts Utility issue, this one features a back made entirely from the shirt backs (the front blocks all are cut from the arms and front panels). I decided including the clothing labels would be fun, too. I used my #courthousecolourplay technique, which is a playful, intuitive way to make these free-cut courthouse blocks. 
👰🤵‍♂️
The quilt name has double meaning: I free-motion quilted their vows right into the quilt with a variegated blue to white @aurifilthread 50 wt. I like how the quilted letters fade in and out depending on the fabric colour. It’s a cuddle on the couch size at 53” x 75” and intended to be loved and enjoyed at their summer retreat cabin.
👰🤵‍♂️

The next time you see this #evadress it will be on me, in Australia!!!
👗 
I was introduced to this one wonderful pattern by @lorena_in_syd who took me to  @tessutifabrics to purchase it when I visited Sydney in 2017. This is my third one and if I can squeeze it in, I plan to make another to take along. It’s such a flattering cut and cool to wear on hot days.
👗 
Fabric is a lovely lightweight “Fine Lines” linen by @blackbirdfabrics but it’s currently out of stock I think.
👗
My two mods were adding an inch to the bodice width (this is a Med) to accommodate chest and shortening the lower skirt by 1.5” so I can walk my normal long gait. The original pattern is too long for me, so the narrow hemline of the skirt lantern shape hinders my stride!

Next up in the linen travel wardrobe is this #evadress hack. It’s very difficult for me to find a tank pattern that works for my armpit circumference. Since I know the tunic part of the dress fits me perfectly without any gaping in the back or pulling in the armpit, I decided to turn it into a loose tank top! I added 7” length to the back and 6” to the front tunic patterns as well as an extra inch at the side seams of the front and back (so 4” extra in the width for a loose top that will skim hips, not hug).

☀️

I love this lawn bias trim so much, but can’t for the life of me remember where I bought it. If anyone knows where I can find it please advise!

☀️

Eva dress pattern from @tessutifabrics

Although they’re made from the same linen as the tank in my previous post, it’s unlikely I’ll wear the top and trousers at the same time (a little too pyjama-adjacent?). These are heavily modified @sewhouse7 #freerangeslacks version 2 as recommended by a fellow flat-seated sewist. After making a toile size 12 with flat seat adjustment graded to a 10, they were still way too baggy in the seat and front thigh.

☀️

I ended up making the linen pair with the following mods (keeping in mind that I do not like, nor want, baggy elastic-waist trousers that fall from fullest tummy straight to the floor):
•traced size 10
•flat seat adjustment graded to size 6 back crotch
•front crotch adjustment graded to size 8
•reduced rise by 1.5” 
If you’re making this pattern with fabric that doesn’t have a noticeable right/wrong side, take great care to sew the side panels in correctly! Also I don’t love how the top of the pocket edge becomes part of the waist band (so bulky!) but I couldn’t think of how to redesign this so I just left it.

☀️

I’ll post wearing pics at some point - these slacks probably fit closer than the intended design but I prefer this fit. I might increase to size 8 in the back crotch on the next pair. I’m glad to have this flat-seat adjustment knowledge now! I still find patterns in general very wacky with sizing for my body shape. If I went with my waist measurement, I would be in a size 18 according to the pattern 🤪. This company actually provides finished garment measurements that helped me decide where to start with my toile.

It’s gonna be a blue day! I’m so happy that the indigo banana vat that I set on July 25 l, 2022 is still going strong! A visiting friend is excited to dye 6 organic cotton napkins (purchased at Maiwa Granville Island). She folded, clamped and stitched her pieces yesterday. 

💙

I kept the vat (covered) outside all winter, checking on it a few times to make sure there was no mould and the pH remained above 9. I revived the vat yesterday by heating to 120°F and added some more fresh banana ‘juice’, a bit more (equal parts) powdered natural indigo and Calx. This morning all signs are good. Ready to dip!

💙

I took lots of time to stare at my design wall, auditioning the placement of pieced units and larger pieces of solid colour. Then the hard work of puzzling it all together with connecting seams. It can be tedious and rife with second-guessing, but you’ve just gotta stick with improv.

Here’s another idea: linen bread bags. I simply hem or serge one long edge of a rectangle of linen. Fold short ends WST and serge the side & bottom edges together. I keep and gift my sourdough boules in these bags.

I exhausted my banana vat after 18 months.  An unsuccessful attempt to revive it pushed me to try a new recipe from my #journeyintoindigo course with @maiwaschooloftextiles .

🔵

This is a 40” square portal dyed in my new ferrous vat. Three dips on cotton poplin. My plastic bag probably could’ve been tied more securely but the resulting leakage created the most interesting organic shapes - I just love it! The depth of shade is fantastic. The ferrous vat was so easy to set and much less work than the banana vat. I’m hoping it’ll keep giving me blue for months. More results to come!

🔵

Although I scoured the fabric for an hour, there are still inconsistencies and some “blotchy” areas. I’m not sure why? I tried to keep the fabric moving in the vat and rinsed off organic matter after each dip. Could be the vat wasn’t yet fully reduced (I left it for 22 hours after initial mixing), or I need a larger vessel for bigger pieces so the fabric isn’t crowded. Any suggestions/ideas welcome!

The 4 steps I took to upcycle this corduroy jacket I got for $20 on Marketplace:
•
1. Take 1 ½” out of each side seam while adding a slight inward curve midway from armpit to hem to reduce shapeless boxy look.
•
2. Cut moderate shirt tail curves  into the bottom edge reducing front length by 2”. The original unhemmed, frayed edge was completely straight and too long on me (contributing to shapeless boxy look).
•
3. Serge bottom edge and frayed cuff edges.
•
4. Apply cute Liberty double fold binding (from @the_strawberry_thief ) along bottom edge & cuffs.
•
Total time about an hour.

I’m grateful to two sisters who trusted me with the care and restoration of their mother’s beloved Singer 15-88 treadle and cabinet. No one in the family was able to keep it and I jumped at the chance when it was offered.

💙

Made at the Singer factory in St.Jean (John), Quebec, Canada in 1936, the machine has been with its original family until now. I’ve written dates, names and details shared with me on a note that will remain in the cabinet drawer.

💙

I still need to install the new leather belt (the original was dry-rotted and fell apart). We disassembled & cleaned the cabinet that had lifting veneer (not a solid oak one) and some mould. After a light sand, I painted with blue chalk paint (not sure this was the right product choice, but I’ll live with it) then waxed. I replaced the bobbin cover plate as the original was corroded and rusty. Parts came from @featherweightshop 

💙

We have frequent power outages here and I have a romantic vision that I’ll lift the machine and sew manually on those days. In the meantime, swipe for current display use.

💙

Thank you Rury and Anna for sharing this gift and your family story with me.
